You need to modify your `compare` method.  Change this:

    static &lt;U,T extends Comparable&lt;U&gt;&gt; int compare(T a, U b) {
        return a.compareTo(b);
    }

to this:

    static &lt;U,T extends Comparable&lt;U&gt;&gt; int compare(T a, U b) {
        if (a == null) {
            return (b == null) ? 0 : -1;
        } else if (b == null) {
            return +1;
        } else {
            return a.compareTo(b);
        }
    }


--------------------------

&gt; Client specifically doesn&#39;t want any if equals null or if (a == null) comparisons. Why can&#39;t we simply use `Comparator.nullsFirst` as it already does what we want?

Because it doesn&#39;t work.  

(Correction: actually it would as [@AndreyB.Panfilov](https://stackoverflow.com/users/3426309) commented on a now deleted answer:  

    return Comparator.nullsFirst(Comparator.&lt;T&gt;naturalOrder()).compare(a, b);

But that doesn&#39;t invalidate what I am about the say next.)

Sometimes client requirements are just so stupid that you have to push back.  You need to educate the client.  Seriously.  It is in *their best interests* to try.

But if you really have a client who insists beyond all reason that `null` literals are *The Spawn of Satan* (or something) ... you could implement the `null` check using `Objects.isNull` ([javadoc][1]).


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Objects.html#isNull-java.lang.Object-

**This is the actual solution**: to change an existing compare method which takes two `Comparables` implementing `compareTo`, to also allow for null comparison like `Comparator.nullsFirst` does, without changing the name or signature of the method, and without using any if statements. Simple? =)

Current method:
```java
static &lt;U,T extends Comparable&lt;U&gt;&gt; int compare(T a, U b) {
    return a.compareTo(b);
}
```

Becomes:
```java
static &lt;T extends Comparable&lt;T&gt;&gt; int compare(T a, T b) {
    return Comparator.nullsFirst(Comparator.&lt;T&gt;naturalOrder()).compare(a, b);
}
```
Since for `T extends Comparable&lt;U&gt;` we have `U extends T` which makes `U instanceof T`, so we can substitute `U` for `T` and the method signature remains unchanged.

There was never any need for null comparisons or reinventing a perfectly good wheel. Java can do what you want, most certainly it can, you must just be willing to put in the work.

nJoy

